Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read the Prime Minister’s address for the latest information.

Vanuatu has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Vanuatu, see Return to the UK
Local measures
International borders are closed. There are no restrictions in place on social gatherings. Restaurants, bars and supermarkets are permitted to open as usual, although some are operating a restricted service or have closed altogether in response to falling trade.
International flights in and out of Vanuatu have been suspended since 23 March and are not expected to resume for some time.
Entry and borders
The government of Australia has announced that from 9pm Australia Eastern Standard Time on 20 March, entry to the country will only be permitted to Australian citizens or permanent residents. This follows a similar announcement by New Zealand from 19 March. If you’re resident in Vanuatu, you should be aware of the potential impact of the border closures and flight restrictions on future travel plans. See also Return to the UK
To transit through Australia you need to have applied for exemption. You can find out more information on this and apply here. Please contact our Sydney consulate using the online contact form once you have requested your exemption so we are aware.
The government of New Zealand has put in place strict measures to limit transit through their airports. More information on this is available from Immigration New Zealand.
Border protection measures
The government of Vanuatu has introduced additional border protection and disease surveillance measures in response to the coronavirus outbreak. See also Entry Requirements
Visas
If you hold a short term visa for Vanuatu which is close to expiry, you should report to the Director of Immigration in order to have your visa extended.
Healthcare
Medical care across Vanuatu is not as advanced as you would find in the UK. Access to medical services and the availability of goods could be impaired during the COVID-19 pandemic and while international flights are suspended. You should take these limitations and risks into account when making travel plans. The government of Vanuatu has introduced additional border protection and disease surveillance measures in response to the coronavirus outbreak.
Further information
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
